summary:
Behind the scenes of The Sound of Drums/The Last of the Time Lords (Part Six) 

  Excerpt from Doctor Who Magazine #384 article...
caption:
Behind the scenes of The Sound of Drums/The Last of the Time Lords
(Part Six)

Excerpt from Doctor Who Magazine #384 article by Benjamin Cook:

“My favorite thing is that the Master is as witty as the Doctor,” Russell adds. “Our hero has this fantastic sense of humor, which undercuts any and every enemy, but when the villain is the same, or even wittier, it really makes the Doctor vulnerable. Suddenly, he hasn’t got the best lines. That destabilizes the whole format. It ups the danger and the fear. You find yourself taking the Doctor - and David Tennant - into new territory, which has got to be good for the show.”

David’s feelings toward the Master’s past form are mixed. “You either loved him or hated him,” he considers, “but I think it depended on the individual story. My first memory of the Master would have been in the mid-1970s, when he was a sort of oily dishrag with bulging eyeballs! I remember, when it came on, not knowing who he was, not realizing that historically he had anything to do with the show, because, of course, you didn’t at age six or whatever; you just saw this weird man being all decayed. It was only years later that I realized that he had a bit of history.”

Thank you to everyone who shared set photos!

title: Broadchurch
body:
Broadchurch really got me emotional on another level. I didn’t cry though, I got very close at moments, and it’s not exactly enormously depressing, at least not compared to some other stuff out there.

But that’s exactly why it’s so good: it doesn’t try to be a tear-jerker and doesn’t over-achieve to make you feel like shit.

It just shows reality. And you don’t see reality done so well anymore.

And because it’s so realistic, it’s way, way, way more haunting.

I absolutely couldn’t stop.

The only other series I can compare it to emotionally is ‘Big Little Lies’, and that one won awards left and right.

‘Even though’ it’s British, I think it deserves just as much recognition. This style of story-telling is dying and I’m so happy it’s not dead yet.

title: 'Mad To Be Normal'
body:
‘Mad To Be Normal’

It’s hard to know what to think of ‘Mad To Be Normal’, the story of R D Laing, the Scottish psychiatrist who was the darling of the counterculture of the 1960s. Laing was known for his controversial methods of treating mental health, without the use of electroconvulsive therapy, then the go-to treatment, even though “we don’t know why it works but it does”.

Laing’s controversy went further than…
